1
00:00:08,660 --> 00:00:10,890
How do we treat this?

2
00:00:10,890 --> 00:00:13,500
How do we treat this
issue of climate change?

3
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:16,410
The main thing is to reduce
greenhouse gas emissions.

4
00:00:16,410 --> 00:00:18,540
What we're seeing here is

5
00:00:18,540 --> 00:00:20,715
that in the lighter
version of each color,

6
00:00:20,715 --> 00:00:22,950
we would have the
direct CO_2 emissions

7
00:00:22,950 --> 00:00:24,420
for different sectors.

8
00:00:24,420 --> 00:00:27,090
If there were no mitigation.

9
00:00:27,090 --> 00:00:29,375
We can see for transport,

10
00:00:29,375 --> 00:00:32,875
there would be a steadily
increasing CO_2 emissions,

11
00:00:32,875 --> 00:00:34,800
for buildings as well.

12
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:37,260
Definitely for industry
and electricity,

13
00:00:37,260 --> 00:00:39,500
we also see this trend in

14
00:00:39,500 --> 00:00:41,930
increasing CO_2 emissions
associated with those.

15
00:00:41,930 --> 00:00:47,570
Now AFOLU here stands for the
net effect of agriculture,

16
00:00:47,570 --> 00:00:49,130
forestry, and other land use.

17
00:00:49,130 --> 00:00:50,450
Then there's also

18
00:00:50,450 --> 00:00:53,645
non CO_2 greenhouse gas
emissions that are coming.

19
00:00:53,645 --> 00:00:56,720
But if we have various
mitigation scenarios,

20
00:00:56,720 --> 00:00:59,480
those are the darker
version of each color,

21
00:00:59,480 --> 00:01:03,320
we can see how we can
reduce the CO_2 emissions.

22
00:01:03,320 --> 00:01:06,530
One of the main ones we can
do is for our electricity.

23
00:01:06,530 --> 00:01:08,180
Key measures to achieve

24
00:01:08,180 --> 00:01:10,790
such mitigation goals
include decarbonizing,

25
00:01:10,790 --> 00:01:12,650
so reducing the carbon intensity

26
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:14,480
of electricity generation,

27
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:16,010
as well as efficiency
enhancements

28
00:01:16,010 --> 00:01:17,320
and behavioral changes.

29
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:19,280
In order to reduce
our energy demand

30
00:01:19,280 --> 00:01:21,365
compared to our baseline.

31
00:01:21,365 --> 00:01:24,770
Another thing to think about
in terms of the treatment of

32
00:01:24,770 --> 00:01:26,420
this climate change issue is

33
00:01:26,420 --> 00:01:28,835
addressing CO_2
emissions fairly.

34
00:01:28,835 --> 00:01:31,025
Not just lumping by country

35
00:01:31,025 --> 00:01:33,395
and asking different
countries to meet targets,

36
00:01:33,395 --> 00:01:36,690
but recognizing our per
capita contributions.

37
00:01:36,690 --> 00:01:39,140
In this figure, we can see that

38
00:01:39,140 --> 00:01:40,790
the United States and China have

39
00:01:40,790 --> 00:01:43,175
similar size areas
on this figure.

40
00:01:43,175 --> 00:01:45,245
Which means that they are both

41
00:01:45,245 --> 00:01:47,800
contributing similar
size CO_2 emissions.

42
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:51,005
But because the horizontal axis

43
00:01:51,005 --> 00:01:52,850
is their annual emissions,

44
00:01:52,850 --> 00:01:55,970
and the vertical axis is
the per capita emissions.

45
00:01:55,970 --> 00:01:58,790
We can see that, the
US is emitting per

46
00:01:58,790 --> 00:02:02,105
person double the CO_2
compared to China.

47
00:02:02,105 --> 00:02:04,430
We want to be able to
take that into account

48
00:02:04,430 --> 00:02:07,630
when making global plans
about CO_2 emissions.

49
00:02:07,630 --> 00:02:10,970
That's one example of global
impact climate change,

50
00:02:10,970 --> 00:02:13,445
and it's one we're
struggling with.

51
00:02:13,445 --> 00:02:15,050
I also want to focus on

52
00:02:15,050 --> 00:02:17,725
a different global impact
or ozone depletion.

53
00:02:17,725 --> 00:02:20,600
We can see in our planetary
boundaries figure,

54
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:23,990
that this is one where
we are safely still in

55
00:02:23,990 --> 00:02:25,640
the safe or green zone

56
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:27,665
for our stratospheric
ozone depletion.

57
00:02:27,665 --> 00:02:29,765
We'll look into
why that might be.

58
00:02:29,765 --> 00:02:32,945
The diagnosis about
ozone depletion is that

59
00:02:32,945 --> 00:02:35,675
in the 1970s and '80s,

60
00:02:35,675 --> 00:02:37,850
a lot of things called CFCs or

61
00:02:37,850 --> 00:02:40,580
chlorofluorocarbons
were being emitted

62
00:02:40,580 --> 00:02:42,985
as part of industrial processes.

63
00:02:42,985 --> 00:02:45,395
What would happen is that

64
00:02:45,395 --> 00:02:47,690
the chlorine would get removed,

65
00:02:47,690 --> 00:02:50,545
once it's in the atmosphere,
get removed from the CFC,

66
00:02:50,545 --> 00:02:54,350
and it was then able to
break down the ozone high in

67
00:02:54,350 --> 00:02:58,520
our atmosphere by reacting
with the O_3 ozone molecules,

68
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:00,330
separating off an O.

69
00:03:00,330 --> 00:03:01,730
Then the chlorine
could get free and

70
00:03:01,730 --> 00:03:03,260
do it again and again and again.

71
00:03:03,260 --> 00:03:05,630
Even a small amount of
chlorine could lead to

72
00:03:05,630 --> 00:03:08,405
a huge depletion in ozone
in our stratosphere.

73
00:03:08,405 --> 00:03:12,670
One CFC could break down
100,000 molecules of ozone.

74
00:03:12,670 --> 00:03:16,160
The problem with
this is that the sun

75
00:03:16,160 --> 00:03:18,940
has different types of rays
that can do damage to us,

76
00:03:18,940 --> 00:03:22,040
and the ozone layer
was blocking some of

77
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:23,630
these critical UV rays

78
00:03:23,630 --> 00:03:27,400
from impacting human
and plant health.

79
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:30,825
We were able to measure
this happening.

80
00:03:30,825 --> 00:03:34,040
This graph is showing the
minimum levels of ozone

81
00:03:34,040 --> 00:03:37,170
over Antarctica
through the year 2015.

82
00:03:37,170 --> 00:03:39,260
The lower the
minimum levels are,

83
00:03:39,260 --> 00:03:41,090
the more exposed plants and

84
00:03:41,090 --> 00:03:43,970
animals are to the
harmful UV radiation.

85
00:03:43,970 --> 00:03:46,940
Now we can see a clear
drastic decrease

86
00:03:46,940 --> 00:03:48,185
in the minimum ozone,

87
00:03:48,185 --> 00:03:51,990
which is bad, but then
they flattened out.

88
00:03:51,990 --> 00:03:55,455
The ozone was no longer
decreasing, and so we went up.

89
00:03:55,455 --> 00:03:57,060
How did that happen?

90
00:03:57,060 --> 00:03:58,875
Here's a little timeline.

91
00:03:58,875 --> 00:04:02,270
The key thing is the diagnosis
came before the symptoms.

92
00:04:02,270 --> 00:04:04,760
In 1920s, a scientist
named Dobson was

93
00:04:04,760 --> 00:04:08,165
studying stratospheric
ozone, and in 1974,

94
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:11,150
an article in nature already
characterized this mechanism

95
00:04:11,150 --> 00:04:12,530
of CFCs migrating into

96
00:04:12,530 --> 00:04:14,635
the stratosphere and
releasing chlorine.

97
00:04:14,635 --> 00:04:18,695
In 1985, the British
Antarctic Survey team

98
00:04:18,695 --> 00:04:21,925
had been measuring the ozone
layer already for 18 years,

99
00:04:21,925 --> 00:04:24,330
and they saw the first
visible evidence

100
00:04:24,330 --> 00:04:25,815
that the ozone layer
was depleting.

101
00:04:25,815 --> 00:04:28,430
It was depleted so much they
actually didn't believe

102
00:04:28,430 --> 00:04:31,685
their data until a second
set of data confirmed it.

103
00:04:31,685 --> 00:04:34,310
Then relatively quickly in 1987,

104
00:04:34,310 --> 00:04:36,350
the Montreal Protocol
on Substances

105
00:04:36,350 --> 00:04:38,570
That Deplete the Ozone
Layer is signed.

106
00:04:38,570 --> 00:04:41,000
It became a legally
binding protocol between

107
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,990
24 countries to
reduce CFC emissions.

108
00:04:43,990 --> 00:04:45,710
Kofi Annan, the former

109
00:04:45,710 --> 00:04:47,825
Secretary General of
the United Nations,

110
00:04:47,825 --> 00:04:49,580
said about this, "Perhaps

111
00:04:49,580 --> 00:04:51,920
the single most successful
international agreement

112
00:04:51,920 --> 00:04:54,025
to date has been the
Montreal Protocol."

113
00:04:54,025 --> 00:04:55,850
That that led to

114
00:04:55,850 --> 00:04:58,900
a freeze in the production
and consumption of CFCs,

115
00:04:58,900 --> 00:05:02,140
and it was a success story.

116
00:05:02,140 --> 00:05:06,485
Industrialized countries in
1986 had a huge amount of

117
00:05:06,485 --> 00:05:09,335
ozone depleting
potential each year

118
00:05:09,335 --> 00:05:10,540
that they were emitting,

119
00:05:10,540 --> 00:05:12,935
and that steadily reduced

120
00:05:12,935 --> 00:05:14,240
to a point where we're no

121
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:16,575
longer worried about
the ozone layer.

122
00:05:16,575 --> 00:05:21,310
That was a little bit about
the global impacts category.

123
00:05:21,310 --> 00:05:24,100
Now we're going to talk about
some human health impacts.

124
00:05:24,100 --> 00:05:26,245
One of the dominant
human health impacts

125
00:05:26,245 --> 00:05:28,840
is ambient air pollution.

126
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:31,855
We can see that on this
figure from the Lancet,

127
00:05:31,855 --> 00:05:35,845
which is outlining the
attributable dailies per year,

128
00:05:35,845 --> 00:05:38,530
so disability adjusted
life years per year

129
00:05:38,530 --> 00:05:41,785
for different things that
impact human health.

130
00:05:41,785 --> 00:05:44,785
The biggest one is dietary
risks and inactivity,

131
00:05:44,785 --> 00:05:46,690
which we spent a
lot of time talking

132
00:05:46,690 --> 00:05:49,355
about already related
to food and diet.

133
00:05:49,355 --> 00:05:51,600
But the next two
biggest ones are

134
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:52,905
household air pollution and

135
00:05:52,905 --> 00:05:56,100
ambient particulate matter,
outdoor air pollution.

136
00:05:56,100 --> 00:05:58,685
Those have a huge
impact on human health.

137
00:05:58,685 --> 00:06:01,270
Other things that impacted
our human toxicity,

138
00:06:01,270 --> 00:06:03,925
including indoor
toxicity of chemicals,

139
00:06:03,925 --> 00:06:05,350
photochemical ozone.

140
00:06:05,350 --> 00:06:08,155
We'll talk a little bit more
about ionizing radiation,

141
00:06:08,155 --> 00:06:11,770
noise, occupational
risks and injuries.

142
00:06:11,770 --> 00:06:13,900
One of those dominant things is

143
00:06:13,900 --> 00:06:15,040
the human health impacts due to

144
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:16,810
primary and secondary
particulate matter,

145
00:06:16,810 --> 00:06:18,100
and this is something
that I focused

146
00:06:18,100 --> 00:06:19,660
on a lot in my research.

147
00:06:19,660 --> 00:06:22,960
It leads to 3.2 million
deaths per year,

148
00:06:22,960 --> 00:06:26,170
65% of which actually
occur in Asia,

149
00:06:26,170 --> 00:06:28,150
which is not at all necessary,

150
00:06:28,150 --> 00:06:31,615
the country that's
inducing the PM emissions.

151
00:06:31,615 --> 00:06:33,040
What happens is something

152
00:06:33,040 --> 00:06:35,665
called reactive oxidants stress,

153
00:06:35,665 --> 00:06:38,875
which leads to cardiovascular
and pulmonary diseases,

154
00:06:38,875 --> 00:06:43,150
lung cancer, lower respiratory
infections, and stroke.

155
00:06:43,150 --> 00:06:49,135
The US alone is responsible
for 86,000 deaths per year,

156
00:06:49,135 --> 00:06:53,485
85% of which are
cardiovascular diseases.

157
00:06:53,485 --> 00:06:55,945
Another human health impact

158
00:06:55,945 --> 00:06:58,075
other than particulate matter is

159
00:06:58,075 --> 00:07:03,070
that due to photochemical
oxidation from NOx and VOCs.

160
00:07:03,070 --> 00:07:06,430
NOx is formed when nitrogen
and oxygen that are

161
00:07:06,430 --> 00:07:07,855
already in the air

162
00:07:07,855 --> 00:07:10,090
react together under
high temperatures,

163
00:07:10,090 --> 00:07:13,345
such as in the exhaust of
fossil fuel-burning engines,

164
00:07:13,345 --> 00:07:14,950
and that creates NOx.

165
00:07:14,950 --> 00:07:16,450
NOx can then react with

166
00:07:16,450 --> 00:07:19,180
volatile organic
compounds or VOCs,

167
00:07:19,180 --> 00:07:22,270
which can be emitted
by gasoline as

168
00:07:22,270 --> 00:07:23,620
an antigen pyrogenic source

169
00:07:23,620 --> 00:07:26,320
or biogenic sources like trees.

170
00:07:26,320 --> 00:07:31,285
When sunlight plus NOx plus
VOCs react, they form ozone.

171
00:07:31,285 --> 00:07:32,470
But in this case,

172
00:07:32,470 --> 00:07:35,740
the ozone is close to
where we are rather than

173
00:07:35,740 --> 00:07:37,000
far up above blocking

174
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,730
the sun and it actually has
negative effects on us,

175
00:07:39,730 --> 00:07:41,755
on respiratory
effects for humans

176
00:07:41,755 --> 00:07:45,055
or decreased reduction
in plant productivity.

177
00:07:45,055 --> 00:07:47,050
Those were some examples of

178
00:07:47,050 --> 00:07:49,240
human health impacts
associated with emissions.

179
00:07:49,240 --> 00:07:50,545
Now we'll talk a
little bit about

180
00:07:50,545 --> 00:07:52,810
ecosystem and
biodiversity impacts.

181
00:07:52,810 --> 00:07:55,225
The main example
will give here is

182
00:07:55,225 --> 00:07:57,655
the Lake Erie toxic algae bloom.

183
00:07:57,655 --> 00:07:59,890
This happens when rainfall

184
00:07:59,890 --> 00:08:02,890
washes fertilizer
and manure that we

185
00:08:02,890 --> 00:08:04,720
emit into the environment from

186
00:08:04,720 --> 00:08:06,340
these large farm fields into

187
00:08:06,340 --> 00:08:08,605
streams that all
flow into Lake Erie.

188
00:08:08,605 --> 00:08:10,720
This fertilizer
causes huge amounts

189
00:08:10,720 --> 00:08:12,700
of algae to grow each year,

190
00:08:12,700 --> 00:08:14,635
which can make water
toxic to fish,

191
00:08:14,635 --> 00:08:16,030
wildlife, and people.

192
00:08:16,030 --> 00:08:18,895
As an example, in July 2019,

193
00:08:18,895 --> 00:08:21,505
a severe bloom of
blue-green algae

194
00:08:21,505 --> 00:08:24,535
began spreading across the
western half of Lake Erie.

195
00:08:24,535 --> 00:08:27,370
The dominant organism in
there was a bacteria that

196
00:08:27,370 --> 00:08:30,385
produces a toxin which
can cause liver damage,

197
00:08:30,385 --> 00:08:32,800
numbness, dizziness,
and vomiting.

198
00:08:32,800 --> 00:08:35,485
That's an example of how
our emissions can cause

199
00:08:35,485 --> 00:08:38,620
ecosystem impacts that can
also impact human health.

200
00:08:38,620 --> 00:08:42,910
Now we'll cover the last
category of resource use.

201
00:08:42,910 --> 00:08:46,585
This can include water use,

202
00:08:46,585 --> 00:08:48,835
such as freshwater
biodiversity loss,

203
00:08:48,835 --> 00:08:50,770
or global water crisis

204
00:08:50,770 --> 00:08:52,765
that leads to food
security issues.

205
00:08:52,765 --> 00:08:55,510
Land use, which
can be related to

206
00:08:55,510 --> 00:08:57,895
habitat change as a major driver

207
00:08:57,895 --> 00:08:59,935
of terrestrial
biodiversity loss.

208
00:08:59,935 --> 00:09:01,225
Biotic depletion,

209
00:09:01,225 --> 00:09:04,105
such as overfishing
and marine ecosystems.

210
00:09:04,105 --> 00:09:05,860
Or energy resources,

211
00:09:05,860 --> 00:09:08,890
that's a functional impact
where the renewal rate of

212
00:09:08,890 --> 00:09:10,690
an energy source
is vastly exceeded

213
00:09:10,690 --> 00:09:13,405
and that's why we call
it non-renewable energy.

214
00:09:13,405 --> 00:09:15,940
Here's an example
of how water use

215
00:09:15,940 --> 00:09:18,160
can affect humans
and ecosystems.

216
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:21,085
Water use decreases
the availability

217
00:09:21,085 --> 00:09:23,125
and leads to
competition for water.

218
00:09:23,125 --> 00:09:25,885
For human users that don't
have any adaptation,

219
00:09:25,885 --> 00:09:27,730
there are direct
human health impacts

220
00:09:27,730 --> 00:09:30,130
associated with
lesser, dirtier water.

221
00:09:30,130 --> 00:09:33,880
But many adaptations also
decrease water availability to

222
00:09:33,880 --> 00:09:35,770
have indirect impacts on

223
00:09:35,770 --> 00:09:38,110
human health resources
and ecosystem.

224
00:09:38,110 --> 00:09:40,315
For ecosystems, they
get limited water.

225
00:09:40,315 --> 00:09:42,745
There are, of course, impacts
on ecosystem quality,

226
00:09:42,745 --> 00:09:44,935
both direct and indirect.

227
00:09:44,935 --> 00:09:48,010
The summary of all this is that

228
00:09:48,010 --> 00:09:50,200
the main diagnoses of

229
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:52,690
these global impact
categories that we're

230
00:09:52,690 --> 00:09:55,360
talking about are the
increasing consumption in

231
00:09:55,360 --> 00:09:57,100
developed nations is leading to

232
00:09:57,100 --> 00:10:00,145
pollution and usage of
non-renewable resources.

233
00:10:00,145 --> 00:10:01,870
The negative impacts that are

234
00:10:01,870 --> 00:10:04,150
occurring are unequally
affecting off in

235
00:10:04,150 --> 00:10:06,190
developing nations through

236
00:10:06,190 --> 00:10:08,320
irreversible use of
natural resources,

237
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:10,195
decreasing water quality,

238
00:10:10,195 --> 00:10:12,995
or climate change or
particulate matter.

239
00:10:12,995 --> 00:10:15,120
It's good to realize
that the scale of

240
00:10:15,120 --> 00:10:16,740
these impacts can
range from very

241
00:10:16,740 --> 00:10:18,450
local to global and from

242
00:10:18,450 --> 00:10:21,825
immediate impacts to those
that take decades to manifest.

243
00:10:21,825 --> 00:10:24,135
A key thing here is just to

244
00:10:24,135 --> 00:10:26,085
think globally and act locally,

245
00:10:26,085 --> 00:10:27,570
and use LCA to help make

246
00:10:27,570 --> 00:10:30,610
our actions more
effective. Thank you.